      <div class="prose">

        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>Specialty contractors — electrical, plumbing, HVAC, concrete, framing, roofing, flooring, and other trades — operate differently than GCs. You're typically subcontracting to GCs rather than managing the full project. Your software needs center on estimating accurately, tracking your own job costs, managing your crew, and invoicing your GC clients efficiently.</p>

        <p>Many GC-focused platforms don't serve specialty contractors well. Here's what does.</p>

        <h2>What specialty contractors need from software</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Trade-specific estimating</strong> — Your estimating needs are different from a GC's. Electrical needs conduit runs, outlet counts, and panel schedules. Plumbing needs fixture counts and pipe footage. HVAC needs load calculations and equipment schedules. Generic estimating tools may not match your trade's workflow.</li>
          <li><strong>Job costing by project</strong> — Know whether each job is profitable — labor hours used vs. bid, materials purchased vs. budget</li>
          <li><strong>Crew and timecard management</strong> — Track hours by crew member and allocate to jobs for accurate labor costing</li>
          <li><strong>Invoice and draw billing</strong> — Bill your GC client at milestones or on time and materials</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile field access</strong> — Your crew leads need to log time and complete daily reports from the field</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Best options for specialty contractors</h2>

        <h3>Contractor Foreman — Best value all-in-one for specialty contractors</h3>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> $49–$249/mo</p>
        <p>Contractor Foreman covers the core needs of specialty contractors at an accessible price: estimating, job costing, time cards, invoicing, scheduling, and subcontractor management. The time card module — with GPS clock-in/clock-out and job allocation — is particularly strong and often cited by trade contractors as the primary reason they use the platform.</p>

        <h3>Fieldwire — Best for field coordination on larger projects</h3>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> Free–$54/user/mo</p>
        <p>If your specialty crews work on commercial projects with multiple subs, Fieldwire lets your foremen access current drawings, submit RFI-style issues, complete daily logs, and manage tasks — often in concert with the GC who's also using Fieldwire. The free tier supports 3 active projects, which works for specialty contractors trialing the tool.</p>

        <h3>Buildertrend — Best for residential specialty contractors who work directly for homeowners</h3>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> $499/mo</p>
        <p>If you're a specialty contractor (remodeling-adjacent roofing, custom millwork, high-end flooring) who works directly for homeowners rather than as a sub to a GC, Buildertrend's client portal and communication tools are worth considering. Most specialty contractors won't need this — it's more relevant for trades that maintain direct client relationships.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>Buildertrend</strong> — For specialty contractors who work directly with homeowners, the client portal and selections tools are genuinely useful.</p>
          <a href="https://www.buildertrend.com" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank" class="btn">Visit Buildertrend →</a>
        </div>

        <h3>Raken — Best for daily reports and safety documentation</h3>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> $15–$25/user/mo</p>
        <p>For specialty contractors whose foremen spend too much time on paperwork, Raken's voice-to-text daily logs and safety documentation tools are a direct time saver. Many specialty contractors use Raken alongside Contractor Foreman or their accounting software rather than as a standalone PM platform.</p>

        <h2>Trade-specific considerations</h2>

        <h3>Electrical contractors</h3>
        <p>Electrical estimating has significant trade-specific depth (panel schedules, conduit fill, NEC code compliance checks). Dedicated electrical estimating software (ServiceTitan, Accubid, ConEst) may be more appropriate for larger electrical contractors. For smaller electrical contractors who don't bid complex commercial work, Contractor Foreman's estimating is sufficient.</p>

        <h3>Plumbing and HVAC contractors</h3>
        <p>Plumbing and HVAC businesses often blend service work (dispatch, warranty, small repairs) with construction work (new installations, tenant finish). For the service side, field service management tools (ServiceTitan, Jobber, Housecall Pro) are purpose-built. For the construction side, general construction PM tools work well. Many HVAC/plumbing contractors run separate software for service and construction rather than trying to find one tool that does both.</p>

        <h3>Concrete, framing, and structural trades</h3>
        <p>These trades typically work as subs on GC-managed projects. The software needs are primarily: accurate estimating, labor tracking, and clean invoicing. Contractor Foreman or a combination of Raken (daily logs) + QuickBooks (financials) often covers the base.</p>

        <h3>Roofing contractors</h3>
        <p>Roofing has a hybrid model — insurance restoration work, retail replacement, and commercial roofing each have distinct workflows. AccuLynx and Roofr are roofing-specific platforms that handle aerial measurements and insurance documentation. For general project management, JobTread and Contractor Foreman work well for roofing operations.</p>

        <h2>What to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Overcomplicated GC platforms</strong> — Procore and Buildertrend are designed for GC workflows that include owner-facing features specialty contractors don't need. Don't pay for features that don't apply to your business model</li>
          <li><strong>Generic project management tools</strong> — Monday.com, Asana, and similar tools lack construction-specific features like job costing, lien waiver tracking, and AIA billing formats</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring mobile</strong> — Your crew is in the field. Whatever you implement needs to work on a phone without extensive training</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <h3>Do specialty contractors need construction software or field service software?</h3>
        <p>Depends on your business mix. If you primarily do construction work (projects, not service calls), construction PM tools are the right fit. If you do significant service and repair work (dispatching crews for same-day calls, warranty work, maintenance contracts), field service software (Jobber, ServiceTitan) handles the scheduling and dispatching side better. Many specialty contractors need both categories.</p>

        <h3>What's the most important feature for specialty contractor software?</h3>
        <p>Labor cost tracking. Most specialty contractors underestimate labor — the difference between a profitable specialty job and an unprofitable one is usually labor hours. Software that tracks actual hours by job against your bid hours, and alerts you when you're running over, gives you the visibility to course-correct before a job eats your margin.</p>

